-- by Jon Bakken at Wed Mar 30 14&#58;49&#58;03 UTC 2011</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='10113#1300812214'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2011-03-22T16:43:34+00:00">Mar 22, 2011 04:43 PM UTC</time> by <b>OSG-GOC</b><a class="anchor" name="1300812214">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Hi Burt,
I understand the situation. Currently the only way CMS foresees to submit MUPJ is via the glidein-WMS but better we are sure we set up the sites in the correct way because this may change in the future and in any case we should protect the system from misuse. We will shortly set up SAM/Nagios tests for pilots and these will probably be submitted not via the glidein-WMS.

As for the current situation we may close the ticket and follow this up &#39;offline&#39; since we all agree it is not critical. BTW&#58; do you know when an upgrade in the glexec version on OSG is foreseen? Version 0.8 also fixes another bug which again is not critical if the system is used through the glidein-WMS but it is worth to have to get a more uniform setup at sites.

Thanks, Claudio
-- by Claudio Grandi at Tue Mar 22 16&#58;37&#58;08 UTC 2011</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='10113#1300810024'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2011-03-22T16:07:04+00:00">Mar 22, 2011 04:07 PM UTC</time> by <b>Burt Holzman</b><a class="anchor" name="1300810024">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Also I wanted to add -- for the Tier 1 @ FNAL, this functionality is not critical.  We run production jobs (single-user pilot, so no gLexec required), and glideinWMS jobs (require gLexec, but internally handles setting the right environment for the payload proxy).  Do you have a CMS use case -- gLexec outside of glideinWMS -- that needs this functionality?</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='10113#1300807621'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2011-03-22T15:27:01+00:00">Mar 22, 2011 03:27 PM UTC</time> by <b>Burt Holzman</b><a class="anchor" name="1300807621">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Hi Claudio,

This behavior depends on gLexec versions -- OSG is still at gLexec 0.6.8-3, where the default behavior does not reset X509_USER_PROXY.
To simulate this, before you run glexec, try the following&#58;

export GLEXEC_SOURCE_PROXY=${GLEXEC_CLIENT_CERT}
export GLEXEC_TARGET_PROXY=/tmp/x509up_u&#96;id -u&#96;.glexec.${RANDOM}</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='10113#1300785958'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2011-03-22T09:25:58+00:00">Mar 22, 2011 09:25 AM UTC</time> by <b>OSG-GOC</b><a class="anchor" name="1300785958">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>After invoking glexec on the WN, the value of $X509_USER_CERT in the payload process is still pointing to the pilot proxy, while it should point to the payload proxy. This behavior has been observed on many OSG sites so it may be a problem in the standard OSG configuration.

